name: NPR
text:
An NPR report revealed the Trump administration awarded over $6 billion in vaccine contracts through a third party. Government contracts executed this way aren't required to include taxpayer protections. 

Now, it faces calls to disclose those contracts. https://t.co/FHEOk5iPSE

text:

text:

Now, he's changed his position and is pushing forward with Amy Coney Barrett's confirmation. https://t.co/uGtIjXBcNZ

name: NPR
text:
The Senate Judiciary Committee begins up to four days of hearings Monday on President Trump's nomination of Amy Coney Barrett to the U.S. Supreme Court.

If confirmed, Barrett, 48, would replace the late Ruth Bader Ginsburg on the high court. https://t.co/KyojyaRRbv

name: NPR
text:
Utah Republican Sen. Mike Lee, who tested positive for coronavirus following a White House event for Supreme Court nominee Amy Coney Barrett, returned to the Capitol on Monday.

It was unclear if Lee had tested negative for the illness before attending. https://t.co/JHjuAZp7fZ

name: NPR
text:
Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., will preside over the hearings, which are expected to last four days. 

The panel is expected to vote on Oct. 22, which will be followed by a floor vote by the end of the month. https://t.co/DuD8qMq9Kb

name: NPR
text: Democrats blasted efforts to move forward with Amy Coney Barrett's nomination so close to Election Day in Monday's hearing. "There's nothing unconstitutional about this process," Republicans argued. https://t.co/DIPNtCmuZx

text: The confirmation hearings for Judge Amy Coney Barrett begin today, amid a pandemic and against the backdrop of early voting that has begun in many states and just 22 days before Election. https://t.co/HUFG4dO3jB

text:
